155
00:15:43,183 --> 00:15:59,577
So a little history back in 1967, to allow for the building of this high school, there was a land swap done between the Metropolitan District Commission, that is now known as DCR, Department of Conservation Resources, and Mississippi.

156
00:16:00,484 --> 00:16:05,508
So in that deal, there were swapping of various parcels, which you'll see in the next slide.

157
00:16:06,909 --> 00:16:15,136
And along with those parcels that were conveyed by, say, now DCR, there were some restrictions on use.

158
00:16:15,236 --> 00:16:18,438
What could be done on those pieces of land?

159
00:16:18,999 --> 00:16:20,560
Specifically, no buildings.

160
00:16:21,141 --> 00:16:27,546
They were meant to be held for athletics and recreation, which is DCR's mission.

161
00:16:28,640 --> 00:16:34,766
Um, that restriction does have a 999 year term to it.

162
00:16:34,886 --> 00:16:39,289
And if you can do the math in your head, add it to 1967.

163
00:16:39,510 --> 00:16:44,014
And so we've got some challenges with the site as we now know.

164
00:16:44,774 --> 00:16:45,195
The next.

165
00:16:46,836 --> 00:16:54,543
So the green highlighted areas are the parcels that were conveyed by DCR to the city.

166
00:16:55,564 --> 00:16:55,664
Um,

167
00:16:57,307 --> 00:17:03,331
The city gate to DCR is not really highlighted, but it is to the northeast.

168
00:17:03,872 --> 00:17:09,636
And again, those are areas that are restricted from building buildings into that.

169
00:17:11,078 --> 00:17:20,805
As part of the feasibility study, the team did bring on a land survey team, and many of you talked about the survey quite a bit.

170
00:17:21,686 --> 00:17:24,208
It was a tremendous undertaking.

171
00:17:24,862 --> 00:17:35,650
more than four months of work that included both research, a ton of field work, and then a lot of confirming work.

172
00:17:35,670 --> 00:17:44,477
And what happens in the early part when they started onto the project back in November, they pulled all of the information and they started with the plans.

173
00:17:44,957 --> 00:17:53,584
The plans helped them map out a way to approach the field work, which again took months of time.

174
00:17:54,280 --> 00:18:02,325
Those plans help them to locate monumentation and do all of the drone work, the field work, etc.

175
00:18:02,345 --> 00:18:07,208
A draft survey was provided to us in February.

176
00:18:08,818 --> 00:18:12,821
And once that work was done, they turned back to the written deeds.

177
00:18:14,002 --> 00:18:18,926
And that is where that language around the restriction sits.

178
00:18:19,847 --> 00:18:30,556
So the SIRTE team was not aware of it themselves until end of February, early March is best we can ascertain from talking to Brennan.

179
00:18:32,173 --> 00:18:39,037
However, in the meantime, we did learn from DCR, we've been having good communication coordination with DCR for the past two months.

180
00:18:39,657 --> 00:18:46,161
DCR was the entity that brought this to the project team's attention on April 28th.

181
00:18:47,281 --> 00:18:56,286
And of course, you're all well acquainted with the process of winnowing down the 29 PDP options to six in March.

182
00:18:56,806 --> 00:18:58,027
You saw some development.

183
00:18:58,707 --> 00:19:02,309
of those six options at the meeting on April 27th.

184
00:19:03,949 --> 00:19:08,852
But of course, now that affects those options that you last saw in April.

185
00:19:09,872 --> 00:19:26,440
So the three options that are not affected by the restriction are A1, the code upgrade, essentially the bounds of the existing building, B1.2, and D1.1, which builds on the southern portion of the site.

186
00:19:28,542 --> 00:19:53,071
next and then the three that do impinge on restricted areas are c 2.2 c 3.4 and d 2.1 which is you know so what the team has done since and also informed by what we heard between meeting last monday of strong preference

187
00:19:53,724 --> 00:19:59,806
